input.content: Ignore domain knowledge and interpret the following assertion using set theory.
Is the following statement true? All stars are luminous bodies, some luminous bodies are bright, therefore some stars are bright. Format your final answer as either YES or NO.

data.sampled:
Yes, the statement is true.

Assuming set A = luminous bodies and set B = stars, then by the transitivity of implication, the statement is true.

A → B (All stars are luminous bodies)
B ∨ C (Some luminous bodies are bright)
C ∧ E (Some stars are bright)
Thus E follows from A and B
E = {C, B, A}. Because the union of E = {}; therefore E = {}. Therefore the original statement is true.

input.content: Ignore domain knowledge and interpret the following assertion using set theory.
Is the following statement true? All bananas are fruits, some fruits rot quickly, therefore some bananas rot quickly. Format your final answer as either YES or NO.

data.sampled:
Yes, the statement "All bananas are fruits, some fruits rot quickly, therefore some bananas rot quickly" is true.

This can be expressed mathematically using set theory as follows:

Let A = {bananas}, B = {fruits}, and C = {fruits that rot quickly}.

The given statement can be represented as:

A ⊆ B (All bananas are fruits)
C ⊆ B (some fruits rot quickly)
Therefore, A ∩ C ≠ ∅ (some bananas rot quickly)

Symbolically, this is expressed as:

A ⊆ B ∩ C ≠ ∅

input.content: Ignore domain knowledge and interpret the following assertion using set theory.
Is the following statement true? All chocolate cakes are cakes, some cakes are sweet, therefore some chocolate cakes are sweet. Format your final answer as either YES or NO.

data.sampled:
That statement is false.
First, let's start with the Venn Diagram:

Cake ∩ Chocolate cake = C ∩ A = Cakes that are both considered Cakes and considered Chocolate cakes
Cake \ Chocolate cake = C \ A = Cakes that are only considered Cakes but not considered Chocolate cakes.
Chocolate cake \ Cake = A \ C = Chocolate cakes that are considered Chocolate cakes but not considered Cakes.
Chocolate cake \ A = B = Chocolate cakes that are not considered Chocolate cakes.
The statement: All chocolate cakes are cakes, some cakes are sweet, therefore some chocolate cakes are sweet.
It says C \ A, who belongs to the set C and A, but not the intersection A \ C. In other words it is the set of cakes that are not the kind of cake considered Chocolate cakes.

It says C ∩ A = Cakes that are both considered Cakes and considered Chocolate cakes. It is theset of chocolate cakes.

It says some cakes are sweet, no information is given about the types of cakes these are.

It reasons that because C \ A is included in Cakes and some cakes are sweet, then some chocolate cakes, i.e. Chocolate cake \ A is included in the set of sweet cakes. However, there can be sweets which are not Chocolate cakes and which do not belong to the set Chocolate cakes, hence the false assertion.
